WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.720
Hello, my name is Colin Rendell, and I'm a professor at Duke University in the Department

00:00:09.720 --> 00:00:13.640
of Statistical Science, and I've been teaching data science with R for a decade now.

00:00:13.640 --> 00:00:18.040
And I've been teaching Shiny specifically to our students since 2015.

00:00:18.040 --> 00:00:21.559
This year at PositConf, I'm teaching a one-day workshop on developing and deploying Shiny

00:00:21.559 --> 00:00:22.559
Dashboards.

00:00:22.559 --> 00:00:25.879
Here are three reasons why you should consider taking this workshop.

00:00:25.879 --> 00:00:28.719
The first reason is to level up your Shiny skills.

00:00:28.719 --> 00:00:32.080
This is a workshop that is designed for our users who already have some basic experience

00:00:32.080 --> 00:00:34.720
with Shiny and are looking to improve their existing skills.

00:00:34.720 --> 00:00:39.360
We'll briefly review basic Shiny concepts around reactivity and app development, but

00:00:39.360 --> 00:00:45.119
we'll quickly expand beyond that into topics like dynamic user interfaces, modularization,

00:00:45.119 --> 00:00:47.320
and customization.

00:00:47.320 --> 00:00:50.639
With that said, the second reason you should take this is to learn how to customize your

00:00:50.639 --> 00:00:54.639
existing Shiny apps and make them look unique.

00:00:54.639 --> 00:00:58.279
One of the most powerful aspects of Shiny is that the app interface is just a webpage,

00:00:58.279 --> 00:01:02.040
and therefore pretty much anything that you can do with HTML, you can do with Shiny.

00:01:02.040 --> 00:01:07.080
And so in that vein, what we'll be discussing is various dashboard interfaces for Shiny.

00:01:07.080 --> 00:01:08.239
There's a lot of options out there.

00:01:08.239 --> 00:01:11.599
We'll talk about how they're different, how they're similar, and how they're implemented.

00:01:11.599 --> 00:01:14.519
And once you understand how they're implemented, that gives you an idea about how you then

00:01:14.519 --> 00:01:16.919
can customize them yourself.

00:01:16.919 --> 00:01:20.720
In so doing, we'll also be touching on the larger Shiny extension ecosystem and how you

00:01:20.720 --> 00:01:24.839
can use that to further customize your app and simplify your own code.

00:01:24.839 --> 00:01:27.160
And then finally, we'll also be talking about options for theming.

00:01:27.160 --> 00:01:30.919
So in particular, if you're working on a Shiny app for a client, how you can customize

00:01:30.919 --> 00:01:35.760
your app to match your client's branding or other kinds of preferences for how it looks.

00:01:35.760 --> 00:01:39.980
Finally, we'll also have a segment discussing about deploying your Shiny apps.

00:01:39.980 --> 00:01:43.160
We'll have a detailed discussion of what options are available for you to do this.

00:01:43.160 --> 00:01:48.199
We'll touch on the whole range of options, including things like Shinyapps.io, PositConnect,

00:01:48.199 --> 00:01:51.919
and even options around self-hosting it, what the limitations of each of these are, what

00:01:51.919 --> 00:01:54.400
the advantages are, and so on and so forth.

00:01:54.400 --> 00:01:59.800
If any of this sounds interesting to you, I encourage you to go to posit.com.conference

00:01:59.800 --> 00:02:03.160
to find more details about this workshop and all the other workshops that are being offered

00:02:03.160 --> 00:02:04.800
during the conference.

00:02:04.800 --> 00:02:09.600
That's also where you'll be able to enroll in this and any of the other available workshops.

00:02:09.600 --> 00:02:12.160
I look forward to seeing you all in Chicago in September.

